The Face Detailer is basically another refiner but it will only apply to the face.

<-- Steps can be 6-12

<-- CFG should remain 1.0

<-- LCM

<-- Karras, Exponential, or Beta

<-- Denoise depends on how far the face is from the camera. If it is close then you want to keep denoise low at 0.7-0.15. If the face is farther away and needs more detail added then a higher denoise of 0.2-0.35 may be needed. There is some trial and error to find the right setting but keeping it always at 0.15 can also be a good strategy if you don't want to mess with it.

<-- Change scale_by to the desired upscale amount.

Example, 1.50 would increase the base image by 50%. So 832x1216 would become 1248x1824.
The Eye Detailer is very similar to the Face Detailer but is specific to the eyes which I think tend to still need a little extra help at this point in the workflow.
<-- This model is responsive to the CLIP Skip setting so it may be worth trying anything from -1 to -5 although -2 should be the default.

<-- Steps can be 6-12

<-- CFG 1.0-1.3

<-- LCM is best for DMD models

<-- Can be Karras, Exponential, or Beta

<-- 0.20-0.50 is a good range depending on how much extra detail you want to apply to the base image. Finding the optimal setting can depend on the image and seed so it may take a little trial and error. It's a good strategy to keep a fixed seed in the base image and try different denoise settings in the refiner sampler until you find the denoise that works best for you.

<-- If your machine can handle higher base generations then you can override the width/height to something like 1024x1536 and maybe keep the scale_by in the upscaler to 1.25. The benefit of this is that you get more detail in the base image and can therefore keep the denoise lower in the refiner. Many times this can give the best result in my experience.

<-- I turn the weight down to 0.8 and raise the start_at to 0.2 because I think this works best for a face transfer that doesn't degrade the image. However, for other types of style transfer you might get better results with weight=1.0 and start_at=0.0.

weight_type has a big impact on the generated image. I normally like style transfer but others may work better depending on the type of style.
<-- This image should have a square 1:1 aspect ratio and contain the the style or face that you want to transfer to the generated image.

<-- Steps should be 6-14

<-- CFG should be 1.0-1.3

<-- lcm is the best option 

<-- karras, exponential, beta or beta57
<-- The right preset depends on the type of style image. I normally leave it on PLUS FACE but sometimes other settings work better.
